g.text: 1) You don't define fixed ip addresses in kubernetes for internal services
(even LoadBalancer gets an ip assigned automatically). Everything works through DNS.
Usually kube-proxy is used, but exoscale uses calico (see exoscale docs)
2) all microservices have their own github repository with a deployment.yaml,
where the exposed port is shown. For every lynus service it is usually 8000
In general, the deployment.yaml of each repository/microservice will explain a lot regarding networking, environment variables, etc.
And if you want to know how the stuff is built, simply inspect the Dockerfile
* empa has nothing to do with empa.ch anymore, the name
is just historical. Empa is used to interact with mqtt or the database,
because it's a pain to handle that in python (ml part), golang is better
